INTRODUCTION.

The family to which the defendant, Lucius Licinius Murena,1 belonged, came originally from Lanuvium, a municipium (see Î¾ 42) about sixteen miles from Rome, which was also the native town of Milo, and the place where the celebrated actor Roscius was educated. After the final subjugation of Latium in Rc. 338, it seems to have been treated with greater consideration than the other Latin towns : the Roman citizenship was conferred on its inhabitants, and they were allowed to retain their ancient rights and privileges.2 As an independent municipium, it faithfully supported the Romans, notably in the Second Punic War.
